master.notes: Selections originally recorded for the "Kraft Music Hall" radio program."Kraft Music Hall" was a popular variety program which aired on NBC radio from 1933-1949.Al Jolson dotted the "Kraft Music Hall" landscape, first as an occasional guest from 1933 to 1935, then later as the star and host from 1947 to 1949.

master.notes: Anatomy of a Murder is noteworthy for being one of the first films to extensively feature jazz in the musical score – the entire musical soundtrack was composed by Duke Ellington and Billy Strayhorn and played by Ellington's orchestra. Several of the Ellington band's sidemen, notably Johnny Hodges, Paul Gonsalves, Harry Carney, Russell Procope, and William "Cat" Anderson, are heard prominently throughout the film, and Ellington himself appears briefly as "Pie-Eye," the owner of a roadhouse where Paul Biegler (Stewart) and Laura Manion (Remick) have a confrontation.Despite being heard "in bits and pieces" the score "contains some of his most evocative and eloquent music… and beckons with the alluring scent of a femme fatale." Including small pieces by Billy Strayhorn, film historians recognize it "as a landmark — the first significant Hollywood film music by African Americans comprising non-diegetic music, that is, music whose source is not visible or implied by action in the film, like an on-screen band." The score avoids cultural stereotypes which previously characterized jazz scores and "rejected a strict adherence to visuals in ways that presaged the New Wave cinema of the ’60s."The soundtrack, containing 13 tracks, was released on May 29, 1959. A CD was released on April 28, 1995, and reissued by Sony in a deluxe edition in 1999.Recorded at Radio Recorders, Los Angeles on May 29 and June 1 & 2, 1959.

master.notes: The title "Mozaikdarabkák" is an allusion to the fact that each of the tracks of the album can also be regarded as a separate island or world on its own, since they are all presented with different characters, paces, styles. At the same time, the tiny elements form an organic whole that defines the entity, the music of the band Miegymás. Some of the tracks are inspired by literary pieces by Attila József, William Blake or Sándor Weöres, and as a result the atmosphere of these is perhaps somewhat more melancholic, meditative. As a complete counterpart to the aforementioned quick, gallopping, merry and fresh themes with asymmetric rhythms are scattered here and there along the album, among them a real treasure, the latest composition entitled Attic of Past, authored by the pianist and accompanied by Erika Kertész’s English lyrics.

master.notes: 1952 10" LP compiling recordings from Oct./Nov. 1947 and July 1948 originally released as singles: * Blue Note 543   Thelonious Monk - 'Round Midnight / Well, You Needn't* Blue Note 547   Thelonious Monk - Evonce / Off Minor* Blue Note 548   Thelonious Monk - In Walked Bud / Epistrophy* Blue Note 549   Thelonious Monk - Ruby, My Dear / Evidence* Blue Note 560   Thelonious Monk - Humph / MisteriosoIn 1956 the compilation was expanded for the 12" format with a new cover, adding missing tracks from the above plus one from:* Blue Note 1564   Thelonious Monk - I Mean You / Tadd Dameron - Symphonetteand one previously unreleased track, Introspection.The 1989 CD added outtakes.  The 2001 version was remastered and restored the 1952 cover design.Please use compilation tag.
master.title: Genius Of Modern Music

master.notes: Reconfigured expansion of [m820804] but lacking two tracks.  Compiles songs originally released on: * Blue Note 542 Thelonious Monk - Thelonious / Suburban Eyes * Blue Note 547   Thelonious Monk - Evonce / Off Minor* Blue Note 1565 Thelonious Monk - Who Knows / Monk's Mood * Blue Note 1575 Thelonious Monk - Nice Work If You Can Get It / April In Paris * Blue Note 1589 Thelonious Monk - Four In One / Straight, No Chaser * Blue Note 1591 Thelonious Monk - Ask Me Now / Willow Weep For Me* Blue Note 1602   Thelonious Monk - Skippy / Let's Cool One* Blue Note 1603   Thelonious Monk - Hornin' In / Carolina Moon1989 CD added alternate takes plus two songs not released until the Mosaic box set (Sixteen and I'll Follow You), plus Eronel from * Blue Note 1590   Thelonious Monk - Criss Cross / EronelThe 2001 CD [m986143] was remastered but removed tracks with Milt Jackson, compiled on [r1248094].  It also restored the cover design from the 1952 10" LP.

master.notes: "The Supremes Sing Rodgers & Hart" was originally conceived to be a double album, but it was halved before Motown issued it in 1967. Motown released an expanded CD "The Rodgers & Hart Collection" in 1987 with several more songs included with the original twelve LP tracks. "The Supremes Sing Rodgers & Hart: The Complete Recordings" was released in 2002 that included all of the songs originally intended for the double LP, including a bonus live 'medley' recorded at the Copacabana, NYC. May 19, 1967.This project would be the last time the trio would receive group credit, after this their recordings were released as Diana Ross & The Supremes, these also turned out to be the final studio recordings made by the original lineup. Florence Ballard (Flo) would be replaced by Cindy Birdsong.
